HybridSFSNet is a baseline SFS-inspired model that combines spatial and frequency feature learning for SAR ship detection. The spatial branch uses CNN layers to 
extract ship shape and edge information, while the frequency branch uses FFT-based features to capture SAR texture and scattering patterns. Both features are fused 
using an attention mechanism and passed to a classifier, achieving a best validation accuracy of 98.75%.

To improve this, I proposed MSRFNet++ (Multi-Scale Residual Frequency Fusion Network++). It enhances the baseline by adding multi-scale spatial feature extraction 
using parallel 3×3 and 5×5 convolutions, residual fusion for better integration of frequency features, Batch Normalization for stable training, SE attention for 
suppressing SAR noise, and data augmentation for better generalization. These improvements made the model more robust and practical, achieving a best validation 
accuracy of 99.38%, outperforming the baseline.
